Part 1

The morning shift at the hospital began at six.

The corridors had the grey, cold light of an early dawn that hadn't yet cleared the smoke from the railway yard.

Adarsh walked toward the casualty.

He hadn't slept more than two hours, his eyes carrying the dry, burning sensation of a long night.

The crowd near the ICU door had not dispersed.

They were still there.

The auto driver. The flower seller. The school teacher.

But they were no longer standing in a queue.

They were sitting on the floor, their backs against the green-painted wall, their hands empty.

Nobody was holding flowers today.

Ananya sat on the same chair, the walking stick with the red strip of cloth leaning against her shoulder.

She wasn't looking at the door.

She was looking at the leather slippers kept carefully under the stretcher frame near the wall.

Both slippers. Clean. Placed side by side.

Adarsh slowed his pace.

The ICU door was open.

Inside, the monitor on table nine was silent, the green screen blank, the power cord unplugged and wound around the metal stand.

The sheet on the bed was pulled all the way to the top.

A clean, white hospital sheet, showing only the outline of a thin shoulder and the long frame of the legs.

The senior nurse was standing near the medicine cabinet, sorting the unused ampoules of adrenaline back into the plastic tray.

She saw Adarsh.

She kept the tray down.

"At four-fifteen, sir," she said. "The pressure dropped. We gave the dopamine, but the heart was too tired."

Adarsh stood near the bed.

He didn't pull the sheet back.

As a doctor, he had pulled back a hundred sheets. He had checked the pupils, felt the neck for the carotid, signed the time of death on the margins of the file.

But he didn't touch this one.

He looked at the white outline.

The distance between the anatomy dissection table in 1995 and this silent ICU bed was twenty-three years.

He had spent the night thinking of the questions he would ask when Vikram woke.

*Why didn't you write?*

*Where was the business?*

*Who was Rehman?*

Now, the sheet was closed.

The questions had stayed in his head, and there was no other room where the answers would be spoken.

"A lady is waiting in the visitor's room," the nurse said, keeping the adrenaline box in the drawer.

"Dr. Sen. The psychiatrist from the Kolkata medical college. She had the patient's records from 2016."

Adarsh looked at the white sheet one last time.

Then he turned.

He walked out of the ICU, passed the crowd sitting against the wall, and went toward the visitor's wing.

The old tea seller at the corner of the corridor was starting his stove.

The blue flame groaned as it caught the coal.

Smelling of kerosene and the dry, cold air of the morning.

[End of Part 1]
